PARTICIPANT INFORMATION SHEET


Project title: Economic decision-making

Name of Principal Investigator/Supervisor (PI): Professor Quentin Atkinson

Name of Student Researcher(s): Scott Claessens



Researcher introduction

Our research team consists of Scott Claessens (PhD student in Psychology at the University of Auckland; s.claessens@auckland.ac.nz) and Professor Quentin Atkinson (Professor in the School of Psychology at the University of Auckland; q.atkinson@auckland.ac.nz). This research is funded by a Royal Society of New Zealand Marsden Fund grant.



Project description and invitation

We would like to invite you to take part in our research studying how people make economic decisions. We are interested in how people make decisions involving money, and how these decisions relate to other attitudes and values. You have been invited to participate through the online platform Prolific. Participation in this study is voluntary. You must be at least 18 years old to participate in this study.



Project procedures

This study consists of a 30 minute online survey. In the survey, you will answer some questions about your attitudes and values, and make some decisions involving money. You will earn a base rate of £3.75 for taking part. The decisions made by yourself and other study participants will determine your additional bonus payment (between £0.60 and £4.90). You will not learn the identity of any of the other study participants at any point either during or after the conclusion of the study, and they will not learn your identity. There are no known physical or psychological risks associated with this research.



Data storage/retention/destruction/future use

The data will be used for a PhD thesis, and to generate results for publication in scholarly journals. Data will be stored in a confidential de-identified electronic format. All journals now require that such data be made available to interested researchers for purposes of replication, verification, and reproducibility. Therefore, after the study, we will publicly post the confidential de-identified dataset online in a public repository (the Open Science Framework) along with our analysis code.



Right to withdraw from participation

Participation in this study is voluntary. You have the right to withdraw from participation at any time during the study without giving a reason. You can also withdraw from the study at a later date by emailing us (s.claessens@auckland.ac.nz). In that case, we will delete any data that you submitted. Should you wish to do this, you must let us know within two weeks of your day of participation (otherwise we will not be able to identify your data in the de-identified dataset). You will need to tell us the date of your participation, as well as your Prolific ID.



Anonymity and confidentiality

Two weeks after the study, we will de-identify the study data by permanently deleting all Prolific IDs from the dataset, as well as any location data (IP addresses, longitude, and latitude). Without this information, nothing will connect your identity to your study data. This confidential de-identified dataset will be used for all analyses and will be posted online in a public repository.



Contact details

If you have any questions or concerns about this today, please contact Scott Claessens (Email: s.claessens@auckland.ac.nz) or Professor Quentin Atkinson (Phone: +64 9 923 4316; Email: q.atkinson@auckland.ac.nz) in the School of Psychology at the University of Auckland. You may also contact Professor Suzanne Purdy, Head of the School of Psychology at the University of Auckland (Phone: +64 9 923 2073; Email: sc.purdy@auckland.ac.nz).



UAHPEC Chair contact details

For any queries regarding ethical concerns you may contact the Chair, The University of Auckland Human Participants Ethics Committee, Office of Research Strategy and Integrity, The University of Auckland, Private Bag 92019, Auckland 1142 (Phone: +64 9 373 7599 ext. 83711; Email: humanethics@auckland.ac.nz).

Feedback:
It was very interesting and now has me wondering exactly what you were trying to discover. I found the first task particularly puzzling. To be told to distribute balls between two crates, but that there was a rule they had to go into crate B? Had to read it several times to figure out the best thing to do. Really wanted to try putting some in Crate A to get more points, but was thinking I might get booted out of the study if I broke the "rule"! 
I'm thinking you are probably looking at political leanings and their correlation with moral/ethical views on the fair distribution of wealth. However, the part where I had to estimate numbers of critters has me a bit stumped. I actually think I'm terrible at visual estimation, so I wonder if this correlates with my feelings about distribution of wealth (!) I actually spent some time counting the number of ladybirds on the example/instructions page, just so it would give me some kind of an idea as to what certain numbers of insecty-things would look like! Felt like that actually helped me make some kind of realistic estimate in the task. Am now hoping you might tell me a bit more about the research on the next page!  Good luck with your project!

But... I think you were looking at correlation between political viewpoints and views about fairness of wealth distribution.
